3. Difference Between Declarative & Scripted Pipelines in Jenkins?

EXPLAIN IN THIS ANSWER:-
â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”
ğŸ”¹ 1. Declarative Pipeline (Recommended for Most CI/CD Use Cases):
ğŸ‘‰ Simpler & More Readable â€“ Uses structured pipeline {} syntax.
ğŸ‘‰ Easier Maintenance â€“ Best for standard CI/CD workflows.
ğŸ‘‰ Supports Declarative Features â€“ Like agent, stages, post, environment.
âœ… Example Declarative Pipeline:
pipeline {
    agent any
    stages {
        stage('Build') {
            steps {
                sh 'mvn clean package'
            }
        }
        stage('Test') {
            steps {
                sh 'mvn test'
            }
        }
        stage('Deploy') {
            steps {
                sh 'kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml'
            }
        }
    }
} 

ğŸ”¹ 2. Scripted Pipeline (More Flexible, Groovy-Based):
ğŸ‘‰ Uses Groovy Syntax â€“ More programmatic and dynamic.
ğŸ‘‰ More Control & Flexibility â€“ Can include loops, conditionals, and complex logic.
ğŸ‘‰ Harder to Maintain â€“ Less readable compared to Declarative pipelines.
âœ… Example Scripted Pipeline:
node {
    stage('Build') {
        sh 'mvn clean package'
    }
    stage('Test') {
        sh 'mvn test'
    }
    stage('Deploy') {
        sh 'kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml'
    }
} 

ğŸ”¹ Real-World Use Case:
ğŸ‘‰ "In my DMS project, we used Declarative pipelines for most CI/CD workflows since they are structured and easy to manage.
    However, for dynamic jobs requiring complex logic, we leveraged Scripted pipelines."
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

4.  What is "Pipeline as Code" in Jenkins?

EXPLAIN IN THIS ANSWER:-
â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”
ğŸ‘‰ "Pipeline as Code in Jenkins means defining CI/CD pipelines using a version-controlled 
    Jenkinsfile instead of manually configuring jobs in the UI. 
    This makes pipelines more scalable, maintainable, automate deployments.

ğŸ”¹ Key Benefits of Pipeline as Code:
âœ… Automation â€“ Eliminates manual job setup.
âœ… Version Control â€“ Pipelines are stored in Git for easy tracking and rollback.
âœ… Consistency â€“ Ensures the same pipeline execution across environments.
âœ… Scalability â€“ Easily replicable for multiple projects.

ğŸ”¹ Real-World Use Case:
ğŸ‘‰ "In my DMS project, we used Pipeline as Code with Jenkins. 
    Every commit triggered an automated CI/CD pipeline, reducing deployment time and improving reliability."
